    <article>
        <articleInfo lang="EN" FirstPage="16" LastPage="27">
            <pdf>26202-jdecp-duke.pdf</pdf>
            <abstract>Predicting recurrence of differentiated thyroid cancer remains an important clinical challenge despite the high efficacy of modern treatment methods. Contemporary machine learning models, including ensemble algorithms (Random Forest, AdaBoost, etc.), demonstrate high accuracy; however, their decisions are difficult to interpret, which limits their practical application in clinical practice. This paper proposes an alternative approach based on anchor instances (precedents) and local metrics, enabling the construction of a minimal, fully interpretable model. Using an open dataset of 383 patients (108 recurrences), 40 anchors were first randomly selected (20 from each class), distances to these anchors were computed in the constructed local metrics, and then a compact solution was obtained via the JRip logical rule extraction algorithm: merely three rules based on distances to four anchor instances. The model achieves 97.13% accuracy under 10-fold stratified cross-validation, outperforming Random Forest (96.34% in our experiments and 95.7% reported in the literature), while maintaining complete transparency: each rule allows direct clinical interpretation. The proposed approach combines high accuracy, sparsity, interpretability, and conciseness, offering an effective tool for clinical decision support.</abstract>
            <title>Interpretable Prediction of Thyroid Cancer Recurrence Based on Anchor Local Metrics and a Minimal Rule Set</title>
            <keywords>
                <word>anchor instances</word>
                <word>ILMR</word>
                <word>interpretable machine learning</word>
                <word>local metrics</word>
                <word>logical rule extraction</word>
                <word>recurrence</word>
                <word>thyroid cancer</word>
            </keywords>
