    <article>
        <articleInfo lang="EN" FirstPage="28" LastPage="38">
            <pdf>26203-jdecp-metrikin.pdf</pdf>
            <abstract>This work is an extension of the author earlier investigations in the nonlinear
                theory of impurity propagation  in solids. Two mathematical models governed
                by partial differential equations are studied. Both models describe
                the dynamics of the impurity propagation in  an infinite homogeneous body
                containing a small impurity source with spherical symmetry. The difference between the models is associated with the impurity source . In the first case the source is assumed to be present during a finite time interval and contains a finite number of impurity particles, whereas in the second case the impurity source is assumed to be stationary and generates an impurity at a constant rate.
                Applying the  approach  based on the dimension rule we transformed the nonlinear partial differential equations into nonlinear ordinary differential equations. The methodology for the formulation of the initial conditions for
                nonlinear ordinary differential equations is presented, and the criteria for
                the evaluation of the correctness of those conditions are formulated. The obtained solutions provide information regarding the time-dependent concentration of the impurities and their finite propagation speed. It is also shown  that the proposed
                approach is  efficient in application to the linear theory of diffusion as well.</abstract>
            <title>Two One-dimensional Boundary Value Problems of Nonlinear Diffusion Theory. Spherical Symmetry</title>
            <keywords>
                <word>dimensional rule</word>
                <word>impurity propagation in a solid</word>
                <word>mathematical model</word>
                <word>nonlinear diffusion theory</word>
                <word>numerical modeling</word>
                <word>partial differential equations</word>
            </keywords>
